Short answer: you can only combine into one flow if the screenshot is already in SharePoint (or in the Teams channel Files folder) at trigger time.
Given your constraints (no premium HTTP; usersâ€™ screenshots are not stored in the Teams channel folder), the screenshot cannot be pulled out of the Teams message and copied into your library in a single flow. The Teams trigger does not give you the file bytes, and without HTTP/Graph you canâ€™t fetch them.

What this means for your two questions

â€œWhy not combine Flow 1 and 2?â€

Combine them only if you change the process so the screenshot is uploaded to your SharePoint library (or the channelâ€™s Files folder) before/at the time of the message. Then one flow can pick up that file/link and write it to the List + Card.

With the current process (inline/attached in a post that isnâ€™t saved to a SharePoint folder you can read), a single flow canâ€™t get the actual image. Thatâ€™s why the â€œmessage recordâ€ link pattern + the separate library watcher (Flow 2) is reliable and 100% standard connectors.

â€œWhen a user posts with a screenshot, does that screenshot get added to the library and the List?â€

As-is: No â€” not automatically, because itâ€™s not in a SharePoint folder the flow can read. Flow 1 will create the message record file (so you always have a SharePoint link) and mark Screenshot Attached? = true.

With Flow 2: As soon as someone (user/tech) uploads the actual screenshot to your library, Flow 2 will update the same List item so Screenshot points to the real image (and keep Screenshot Attached? = true).

If you want it in one flow: Change the process so the screenshot is uploaded to your library (or channel Files) first. Then the one flow can: detect the message, find the corresponding file in SharePoint (by name, by Affected User, or by a pasted link), set Screenshot to that fileâ€™s link, and send the card with a working â€œView Screenshotâ€ button.



